# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: microbiology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] A bacterium, despite its simplicity, contains a well-developed cell structure which is responsible for some of its unique biological structures and pathogenicity.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Many structural features are unique to bacteria, and are not found among archaea or eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Because of the simplicity of bacteria relative to larger organisms and the ease with which they can be manipulated experimentally, the cell structure of bacteria has been well studied, revealing many biochemical principles that have been subsequently applied to other organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Perhaps the most elemental structural property of bacteria is their morphology (shape).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Cell shape is generally characteristic of a given bacterial species, but can vary depending on growth conditions.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Some bacteria have complex life cycles involving the production of stalks and appendages (e.g.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] *Caulobacter*) and some produce elaborate structures bearing reproductive spores (e.g.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Bacteria generally form distinctive cell morphologies when examined by light microscopy and distinct colony morphologies when grown on Petri plates.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Perhaps the most obvious structural characteristic of bacteria is (with some exceptions) their small size.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] For example, *Escherichia coli* cells, an "average" sized bacterium, are about 2 μm (micrometres) long and 0.5 μm in diameter, with a cell volume of 0.6–0.7 μm3.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] This corresponds to a wet mass of about 1 picogram (pg), assuming that the cell consists mostly of water.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The dry mass of a single cell can be estimated as 23% of the wet mass, amounting to 0.2 pg.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] About half of the dry mass of a bacterial cell consists of carbon, and also about half of it can be attributed to proteins.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Therefore, a typical fully grown 1-liter culture of *Escherichia coli* (at an optical density of 1.0, corresponding to c.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] 109 cells/ml) yields about 1 g wet cell mass.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Small size is extremely important because it allows for a large surface area-to-volume ratio which allows for rapid uptake and intracellular distribution of nutrients and excretion of wastes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] At low surface area-to-volume ratios the diffusion of nutrients and waste products across the bacterial cell membrane limits the rate at which microbial metabolism can occur, making the cell less evolutionarily fit.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The reason for the existence of large cells is unknown, although it is speculated that the increased cell volume is used primarily for storage of excess nutrients.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The cell envelope is composed of the cell membrane and the cell wall.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] As in other organisms, the bacterial cell wall provides structural integrity to the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In prokaryotes, the primary function of the cell wall is to protect the cell from internal turgor pressure caused by the much higher concentrations of proteins and other molecules inside the cell compared to its external environment.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The bacterial cell wall differs from that of all other organisms by the presence of peptidoglycan which is located immediately outside of the cell membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Peptidoglycan is made up of a polysaccharide backbone consisting of alternating N-Acetylmuramic acid (NAM) and N-acetylglucosamine (NAG) residues in equal amounts.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Peptidoglycan is responsible for the rigidity of the bacterial cell wall, and for the determination of cell shape.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] It is relatively porous and is not considered to be a permeability barrier for small substrates.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] While all bacterial cell walls (with a few exceptions such as extracellular parasites such as *Mycoplasma*) contain peptidoglycan, not all cell walls have the same overall structures.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] There are two main types of bacterial cell walls, those of gram-positive bacteria and those of gram-negative bacteria, which are differentiated by their Gram staining characteristics.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] For both these types of bacteria, particles of approximately 2 nm can pass through the peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] If the bacterial cell wall is entirely removed, it is called a protoplast while if it's partially removed, it is called a spheroplast.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Beta-lactam antibiotics such as penicillin inhibit the formation of peptidoglycan cross-links in the bacterial cell wall.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The enzyme lysozyme, found in human tears, also digests the cell wall of bacteria and is the body's main defense against eye infections.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Gram-positive cell walls are thick and the peptidoglycan (also known as *murein*) layer constitutes almost 95% of the cell wall in some gram-positive bacteria and as little as 5-10% of the cell wall in gram-negative bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The peptidoglycan layer takes up the crystal violet dye and stains purple in the Gram stain.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Bacteria within the *Deinococcota* group may also exhibit gram-positive staining but contain some cell wall structures typical of gram-negative bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The cell wall of some gram-positive bacteria can be completely dissolved by lysozymes which attack the bonds between N-acetylmuramic acid and N-acetylglucosamine.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In other gram-positive bacteria, such as *Staphylococcus aureus*, the walls are resistant to the action of lysozymes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] They have O-acetyl groups on carbon-6 of some muramic acid residues.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The matrix substances in the walls of gram-positive bacteria may be polysaccharides or teichoic acids.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The latter are very widespread, but have been found only in gram-positive bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] There are two main types of teichoic acid: ribitol teichoic acids and glycerol teichoic acids.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These acids are polymers of ribitol phosphate and glycerol phosphate, respectively, and only located on the surface of many gram-positive bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] However, the exact function of teichoic acid is debated and not fully understood.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Some are lipid-linked to form lipoteichoic acids.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Because lipoteichoic acids are covalently linked to lipids within the cytoplasmic membrane they are responsible for linking and anchoring the peptidoglycan to the cytoplasmic membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Lipotechoic acid is a major component of the gram-positive cell wall.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] One of its purposes is providing an antigenic function.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The lipid element is to be found in the membrane where its adhesive properties assist in its anchoring to the membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Teichoic acids give the gram-positive cell wall an overall negative charge due to the presence of phosphodiester bonds between teichoic acid monomers.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Outside the cell wall, many gram-positive bacteria have an S-layer of "tiled" proteins.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The S-layer assists attachment and biofilm formation.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Outside the S-layer, there is often a capsule of polysaccharides.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The capsule helps the bacterium evade host phagocytosis.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In laboratory culture, the S-layer and capsule are often lost by reductive evolution (the loss of a trait in absence of positive selection).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Gram-negative cell walls are much thinner than the gram-positive cell walls, and they contain a second plasma membrane superficial to their thin peptidoglycan layer, in turn adjacent to the cytoplasmic membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Gram-negative bacteria stain as pink in the Gram stain.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The chemical structure of the outer membrane's lipopolysaccharide is often unique to specific bacterial sub-species and is responsible for many of the antigenic properties of these strains.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In addition to the peptidoglycan layer the gram-negative cell wall also contains an additional outer membrane composed of phospholipids and lipopolysaccharides which face into the external environment.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The highly charged nature of lipopolysaccharides confer an overall negative charge to the gram -negative cell wall.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The chemical structure of the outer membrane lipopolysaccharides is often unique to specific bacterial strains, and is responsible for many of their antigenic properties.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] As a phospholipid bilayer, the lipid portion of the outer membrane is largely impermeable to all charged molecules.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] However, channels called porins are present in the outer membrane that allow for passive transport of many ions, sugars and amino acids across the outer membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These molecules are therefore present in the periplasm, the region between the plasma membrane and outer membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The periplasm contains the peptidoglycan layer and many proteins responsible for substrate binding or hydrolysis and reception of extracellular signals.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The periplasm is thought to exist as a gel-like state rather than a liquid due to the high concentration of proteins and peptidoglycan found within it.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Because of its location between the cytoplasmic and outer membranes, signals received and substrates bound are available to be transported across the cytoplasmic membrane using transport and signaling proteins imbedded there.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Many uncultivated gram-negative bacteria also have an S-layer and a capsule.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These structures are often lost during laboratory cultivation.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The plasma membrane or bacterial cytoplasmic membrane is composed of a phospholipid bilayer and thus has all of the general functions of a cell membrane such as acting as a permeability barrier for most molecules and serving as the location for the transport of molecules into the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In addition to these functions, prokaryotic membranes also function in energy conservation as the location about which a proton motive force is generated.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Unlike eukaryotes, bacterial membranes (with some exceptions e.g.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] *Mycoplasma* and methanotrophs) generally do not contain sterols.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] However, many microbes do contain structurally related compounds called hopanoids which likely fulfill the same function.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Unlike eukaryotes, bacteria can have a wide variety of fatty acids within their membranes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Along with typical saturated and unsaturated fatty acids, bacteria can contain fatty acids with additional methyl, hydroxy or even cyclic groups.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The relative proportions of these fatty acids can be modulated by the bacterium to maintain the optimum fluidity of the membrane (e.g. following temperature change).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Gram-negative and mycobacteria have an inner and outer bacteria membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] As a phospholipid bilayer, the lipid portion of the bacterial outer membrane is impermeable to charged molecules.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These molecules are therefore present in the periplasm, the region between the cytoplasmic and outer membranes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The periplasm is thought to exist in a gel-like state rather than a liquid due to the high concentration of proteins and peptidoglycan found within it.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are protein tubes that extend out from the outer membrane in many members of the *Pseudomonadota*.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] They are generally short in length and present in high numbers about the entire bacterial cell surface.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Fimbriae usually function to facilitate the attachment of a bacterium to a surface (e.g. to form a biofilm) or to other cells (e.g. animal cells during pathogenesis).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] *Myxococcus*) use fimbriae for motility to facilitate the assembly of multicellular structures such as fruiting bodies.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Pili are similar in structure to fimbriae but are much longer and present on the bacterial cell in low numbers.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Pili are involved in the process of bacterial conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or "sex pili".
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Type IV pili (non-sex pili) also aid bacteria in gripping surfaces.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] An S-layer (surface layer) is a cell surface protein layer found in many different bacteria and in some archaea, where it serves as the cell wall.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] All S-layers are made up of a two-dimensional array of proteins and have a crystalline appearance, the symmetry of which differs between species.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The exact function of S-layers is unknown, but it has been suggested that they act as a partial permeability barrier for large substrates.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] For example, an S-layer could conceivably keep extracellular proteins near the cell membrane by preventing their diffusion away from the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In some pathogenic species, an S-layer may help to facilitate survival within the host by conferring protection against host defence mechanisms.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Many bacteria secrete extracellular polymers outside of their cell walls called glycocalyx.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These polymers are usually composed of polysaccharides and sometimes protein.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Capsules are relatively impermeable structures that cannot be stained with dyes such as India ink.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] They are structures that help protect bacteria from phagocytosis and desiccation.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Slime layer is involved in attachment of bacteria to other cells or inanimate surfaces to form biofilms.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Slime layers can also be used as a food reserve for the cell.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Perhaps the most recognizable extracellular bacterial cell structures are flagella.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Flagella are whip-like structures protruding from the bacterial cell wall and are responsible for bacterial motility (movement).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The arrangement of flagella about the bacterial cell is unique to the species observed.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The bacterial flagellum consists of three basic components: a whip-like filament, a motor complex, and a hook that connects them.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The filament is approximately 20 nm in diameter and consists of several protofilaments, each made up of thousands of flagellin subunits.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The bundle is held together by a cap and may or may not be encapsulated.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The motor complex consists of a series of rings anchoring the flagellum in the inner and outer membranes, followed by a proton-driven motor that drives rotational movement in the filament.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In comparison to eukaryotes, the intracellular (internal) features of the bacterial cell are extremely simple.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Bacteria do not typically contain eukaryotic membrane-bound organelles, but often contain other complex intracellular structures.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Unlike eukaryotes, the bacterial DNA is not enclosed inside of a membrane-bound nucleus but instead resides inside the cytoplasm.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The processes concerning the transfer of genetic information — translation, transcription, and DNA replication — therefore all occur within the same compartment and can interact with other cytoplasmic structures, most notably ribosomes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The bacterial DNA is not packaged using histones to form chromatin as in eukaryotes but instead exists as a highly compact supercoiled structure, the precise nature of which remains unclear.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Most bacterial chromosomes are circular, although some examples of linear chromosomes exist (e.g.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Usually, a single bacterial chromosome is present, although some species with multiple chromosomes have been described.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Along with chromosomal DNA, most bacteria also contain small independent pieces of DNA called plasmids that often encode advantageous traits but are not essential to their bacterial host.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Plasmids can be easily gained or lost by a bacterium and can be transferred between bacteria as a form of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] In most bacteria the most numerous intracellular structure is the ribosome, the site of protein synthesis in all living organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] All prokaryotes have 70S (where S=Svedberg units) ribosomes while eukaryotes contain larger 80S ribosomes in their cytosol.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The 70S ribosome is made up of a 50S and 30S subunits.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The 50S subunit contains the 23S and 5S rRNA while the 30S subunit contains the 16S rRNA.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These rRNA molecules differ in size in eukaryotes and are complexed with a large number of ribosomal proteins, the number and type of which can vary slightly between organisms.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] While the ribosome is the most commonly observed intracellular multiprotein complex in bacteria other large complexes do occur and can sometimes be seen using microscopy.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] While not typical of all bacteria, some microbes contain intracellular membranes in addition to (or as extensions of) their cytoplasmic membranes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] An early idea was that bacteria might contain membrane folds termed mesosomes, but these were later shown to be artifacts produced by the chemicals used to prepare the cells for electron microscopy.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Examples of bacteria containing intracellular membranes are phototrophs (ex.: thylakoid), nitrifying bacteria (ex.: anammoxosome) and methane-oxidising bacteria such as the methylococcaceae.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Intracellular membranes are also found in bacteria belonging to the poorly studied Planctomycetota group, although these membranes more closely resemble organellar membranes in eukaryotes and are currently of unknown function.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Chromatophores are intracellular membranes found in phototrophic bacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Used primarily for photosynthesis, they contain bacteriochlorophyll pigments and carotenoids.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The prokaryotic cytoskeleton is the collective name for all structural filaments in prokaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] It was once thought that prokaryotic cells did not possess cytoskeletons, but advances in imaging technology and structure determination have shown the presence of filaments in these cells.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Homologues for all major cytoskeletal proteins in eukaryotes have been found in prokaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Cytoskeletal elements play essential roles in cell division, protection, shape determination, and polarity determination in various prokaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Most bacteria do not live in environments that contain large amounts of nutrients at all times.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] To accommodate these transient levels of nutrients, bacteria contain several different methods of nutrient storage in times of plenty for use in times of want.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] For example, many bacteria store excess carbon in the form of polyhydroxyalkanoates or glycogen.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Some microbes store soluble nutrients such as nitrate in vacuoles.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Sulfur is most often stored as elemental (S0) granules which can be deposited either intra- or extracellularly.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Sulfur granules are especially common in bacteria that use hydrogen sulfide as an electron source.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Most of the above-mentioned examples can be viewed using a microscope and are surrounded by a thin nonunit membrane to separate them from the cytoplasm.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Inclusions are considered to be nonliving components of the cell that do not possess metabolic activity and are not bounded by membranes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The most common inclusions are glycogen, lipid droplets, crystals, and pigments.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Volutin granules are cytoplasmic inclusions of complexed inorganic polyphosphate.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These granules are called metachromatic granules due to their displaying the metachromatic effect; they appear red or blue when stained with the blue dyes methylene blue or toluidine blue.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Gas vacuoles are membrane-bound, spindle-shaped vesicles, found in some planktonic bacteria and *Cyanobacteria*, that provides buoyancy to these cells by decreasing their overall cell density.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Positive buoyancy is needed to keep the cells in the upper reaches of the water column, so that they can continue to perform photosynthesis.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] They are made up of a shell of protein that has a highly hydrophobic inner surface, making it impermeable to water (and stopping water vapour from condensing inside) but permeable to most gases.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Because the gas vesicle is a hollow cylinder, it is liable to collapse when the surrounding pressure increases.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Natural selection has fine tuned the structure of the gas vesicle to maximise its resistance to buckling, including an external strengthening protein, GvpC, rather like the green thread in a braided hosepipe.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] There is a simple relationship between the diameter of the gas vesicle and pressure at which it will collapse – the wider the gas vesicle the weaker it becomes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] However, wider gas vesicles are more efficient, providing more buoyancy per unit of protein than narrow gas vesicles.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The diameter of the gas vesicle will also help determine which species survive in different bodies of water.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Deep lakes that experience winter mixing expose the cells to the hydrostatic pressure generated by the full water column.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] This will select for species with narrower, stronger gas vesicles.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The cell achieves its height in the water column by synthesising gas vesicles.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] As the cell rises up, it is able to increase its carbohydrate load through increased photosynthesis.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Too high and the cell will suffer photobleaching and possible death, however, the carbohydrate produced during photosynthesis increases the cell's density, causing it to sink.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] An extreme excess of carbohydrate causes a significant change in the internal pressure of the cell, which causes the gas vesicles to buckle and collapse and the cell to sink out.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] These "polyhedral organelles" localize and compartmentalize bacterial metabolism, a function performed by the membrane-bound organelles in eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Carboxysomes are bacterial microcompartments found in many autotrophic bacteria such as Cyanobacteria, Knallgasbacteria, Nitroso- and Nitrobacteria.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] They are proteinaceous structures resembling phage heads in their morphology and contain the enzymes of carbon dioxide fixation in these organisms (especially ribulose bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase, RuBisCO, and carbonic anhydrase).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] It is thought that the high local concentration of the enzymes along with the fast conversion of bicarbonate to carbon dioxide by carbonic anhydrase allows faster and more efficient carbon dioxide fixation than possible inside the cytoplasm.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Similar structures are known to harbor the coenzyme B12-containing glycerol dehydratase, the key enzyme of glycerol fermentation to 1,3-propanediol, in some Enterobacteriaceae (e. g.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Magnetosomes are bacterial microcompartments found in magnetotactic bacteria that allow them to sense and align themselves along a magnetic field (magnetotaxis).
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The ecological role of magnetotaxis is unknown but is thought to be involved in the determination of optimal oxygen concentrations.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Magnetosomes are composed of the mineral magnetite or greigite and are surrounded by a lipid bilayer membrane.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The morphology of magnetosomes is species-specific.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Perhaps the best known bacterial adaptation to stress is the formation of endospores.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Endospores are bacterial survival structures that are highly resistant to many different types of chemical and environmental stresses and therefore enable the survival of bacteria in environments that would be lethal for these cells in their normal vegetative form.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] It has been proposed that endospore formation has allowed for the survival of some bacteria for hundreds of millions of years (e.g. in salt crystals) although these publications have been questioned.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Endospore formation is limited to several genera of gram-positive bacteria such as *Bacillus* and *Clostridium*.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] It differs from reproductive spores in that only one spore is formed per cell resulting in no net gain in cell number upon endospore germination.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] The location of an endospore within a cell is species-specific and can be used to determine the identity of a bacterium.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Dipicolinic acid is a chemical compound which composes 5% to 15% of the dry weight of bacterial spores and is implicated in being responsible for the heat resistance of endospores.
[src:microbiology/bacterial-cell-structure] Archaeologists have found viable endospores taken from the intestines of Egyptian mummies as well as from lake sediments in Northern Sweden estimated to be many thousands of years old.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A **biofilm** is a syntrophic community of microorganisms in which cells stick to each other and often also to a surface.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These adherent cells become embedded within a slimy extracellular matrix composed of extracellular polymeric substances (EPSs) produced by them, which are typically a polymeric combination of extracellular polysaccharides, proteins, lipids and DNA.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Because they have a three-dimensional structure and represent a community lifestyle for microorganisms, they have been metaphorically described as "cities for microbes".
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The biofilm allows sharing of nutrients among its residents and serves as a physical barrier against harmful environmental interactions such as desiccation, toxins/antibiotics, bacterivory and attacks from a host body's immune system.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms may form on living (biotic) or non-living (abiotic) surfaces and can be common in natural, industrial, and hospital settings.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They may constitute a microbiome or be a portion of it.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The microbial cells growing in a biofilm are physiologically distinct from planktonic cells of the same organism, which, by contrast, are single cells that may float or swim in a liquid medium.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can form on the teeth of most animals as dental plaque, where they may cause tooth decay and gum disease.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A cell that switches to the biofilm mode of growth undergoes a phenotypic shift in behavior in which large suites of genes are differentially regulated.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A biofilm may also be considered a hydrogel, which is a complex polymer that contains many times its dry weight in water.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are not just bacterial slime layers but biological systems; the bacteria organize themselves into a coordinated functional community, and can begin to form when a free-swimming, planktonic bacterium attaches to a surface and then proliferates monoclonally.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can attach to a surface such as a tooth or rock, and may include a single species or a diverse group of microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Subpopulations of cells within the biofilm differentiate to perform various activities for motility, matrix production, and sporulation, supporting the overall success of the biofilm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are thought to have arisen during primitive Earth as a defense mechanism for prokaryotes, as the conditions at that time were too harsh for their survival.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They can be found very early in Earth's fossil records (about 3.25 billion years ago) as both Archaea and Bacteria, and commonly protect prokaryotic cells by providing them with homeostasis, encouraging the development of complex interactions between the cells in the biofilm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The formation of a biofilm begins with the attachment of free-floating microorganisms to a surface.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The first colonist bacteria of a biofilm may adhere to the surface initially by the weak van der Waals forces and hydrophobic effects.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] If the colonists are not immediately separated from the surface, they can anchor themselves more permanently using cell adhesion structures such as pili.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A unique group of Archaea that inhabit anoxic groundwater have similar structures called hami.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Each hamus is a long tube with three hook attachments that are used to attach to each other or to a surface, enabling a community to develop.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Hyperthermophilic archaeon *Pyrobaculum calidifontis* produce bundling pili which are homologous to the bacterial TasA filaments, a major component of the extracellular matrix in bacterial biofilms, which contribute to biofilm stability.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] TasA homologs are encoded by many other archaea, suggesting mechanistic similarities and evolutionary connection between bacterial and archaeal biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Hydrophobicity can also affect the ability of bacteria to form biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacteria with increased hydrophobicity have reduced repulsion between the substratum and the bacterium.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Some bacteria species are not able to attach to a surface on their own successfully due to their limited motility but are instead able to anchor themselves to the matrix or directly to other, earlier bacteria colonists.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Non-motile bacteria cannot recognize surfaces or aggregate together as easily as motile bacteria.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] During surface colonization bacteria cells are able to communicate using quorum sensing (QS) products such as N-acyl homoserine lactone (AHL).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Once colonization has begun, the biofilm grows by a combination of cell division and recruitment.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Polysaccharide matrices typically enclose bacterial biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The matrix exopolysaccharides can trap QS autoinducers within the biofilm to prevent predator detection and ensure bacterial survival.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In addition to the polysaccharides, these matrices may also contain material from the surrounding environment, including but not limited to minerals, soil particles, and blood components, such as erythrocytes and fibrin.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The development of a biofilm may allow for an aggregate cell colony to be increasingly tolerant or resistant to antibiotics.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Cell-cell communication or quorum sensing is involved in the formation of biofilm in several bacterial species.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are the product of a microbial developmental process.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The process is summarized by five major stages of biofilm development.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The initiation of development starts in the first stage of initial reversible attachment which is initiated by the attachment of planktonic cells to a surface.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This initial attachment is then followed by the second stage of irreversible attachment where further microbial aggregation allows cells to attach to their initial foundation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] After attachment, stages three and four of formation allow for biofilm maturation, characterized by the appearance of cell clusters embedded into a matrix before completing these stages of maturation through the evolution of micro-colonies.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Finally, the fifth stage of development is dispersion, allowing for a fully developed and functional microbial biofilm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Dispersal of cells from the biofilm colony is an essential stage of the biofilm life cycle.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Dispersal enables biofilms to spread and colonize new surfaces.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Enzymes that degrade the biofilm extracellular matrix, such as dispersin B and deoxyribonuclease, may contribute to biofilm dispersal.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Enzymes that degrade the biofilm matrix may be useful as anti-biofilm agents.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Evidence has shown that a fatty acid messenger, *cis*-2-decenoic acid, is capable of inducing dispersion and inhibiting growth of biofilm colonies.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Secreted by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, this compound induces cyclo heteromorphic cells in several species of bacteria and the yeast *Candida albicans*.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Nitric oxide has also been shown to trigger the dispersal of biofilms of several bacteria species at sub-toxic concentrations.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Nitric oxide has potential as a treatment for patients that have chronic infections caused by biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Antibiofilm methods, such as bacteriophages and CRISPR-Cas system, were developed in April 2026 for biofilm dispersal and disruption.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It was generally assumed that cells dispersed from biofilms immediately go into the planktonic growth phase.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] However, studies have shown that the physiology of dispersed cells from *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* biofilms is highly different from that of planktonic and biofilm cells.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Hence, the dispersal process is a unique stage during the transition from biofilm to planktonic lifestyle in bacteria.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Dispersed cells are found to be highly virulent against macrophages and *Caenorhabditis elegans*, but highly sensitive towards iron stress, as compared with planktonic cells.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Furthermore, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* biofilms undergo distinct spatiotemporal dynamics during biofilm dispersal or disassembly, with contrasting consequences in recolonization and disease dissemination.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilm dispersal induced bacteria to activate dispersal genes to actively depart from biofilms as single cells at consistent velocities but could not recolonize fresh surfaces.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In contrast, biofilm disassembly by degradation of a biofilm exopolysaccharide released immotile aggregates at high initial velocities, enabling the bacteria to recolonize fresh surfaces and cause infections in the hosts efficiently.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Hence, biofilm dispersal is more complex than previously thought, where bacterial populations adopting distinct behavior after biofilm departure may be the key to survival of bacterial species and dissemination of diseases.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are usually found on solid substrates submerged in or exposed to an aqueous solution, although they can form as floating mats on liquid surfaces and also on the surface of leaves, particularly in high humidity climates.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Given sufficient resources for growth, a biofilm will quickly grow to be macroscopic (visible to the naked eye).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can contain many different types of microorganism, e.g. bacteria, archaea, protozoa, fungi and algae; each group performs specialized metabolic functions.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] However, some organisms will form single-species films under certain conditions.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The social structure (cooperation/competition) within a biofilm depends highly on the different species present.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The EPS matrix consists of exopolysaccharides, proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A large proportion of the EPS is more or less strongly hydrated, however, hydrophobic EPS also occur; one example is cellulose which is produced by a range of microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This matrix encases the cells within it and facilitates communication among them through biochemical signals as well as gene exchange.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The EPS matrix also traps extracellular enzymes and keeps them in close proximity to the cells.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Thus, the matrix represents an external digestion system and allows for stable synergistic microconsortia of different species.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Some biofilms have been found to contain water channels that help distribute nutrients and signalling molecules.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This matrix is strong enough that under certain conditions, biofilms can become fossilized (stromatolites).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacteria living in a biofilm usually have significantly different properties from free-floating bacteria of the same species, as the dense and protected environment of the film allows them to cooperate and interact in various ways.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] One benefit of this environment is increased resistance to detergents and antibiotics, as the dense extracellular matrix and the outer layer of cells protect the interior of the community.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In some cases antibiotic resistance can be increased up to 5,000 times.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Lateral gene transfer is often facilitated within bacterial and archaeal biofilms and can lead to a more stable biofilm structure.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Extracellular DNA is a major structural component of many different microbial biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Enzymatic degradation of extracellular DNA can weaken the biofilm structure and release microbial cells from the surface.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] However, biofilms are not always less susceptible to antibiotics.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] For instance, the biofilm form of *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* has no greater resistance to antimicrobials than do stationary-phase planktonic cells, although when the biofilm is compared to logarithmic-phase planktonic cells, the biofilm does have greater resistance to antimicrobials.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This resistance to antibiotics in both stationary-phase cells and biofilms may be due to the presence of persister cells.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are ubiquitous in organic life.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Nearly every species of microorganism have mechanisms by which they can adhere to surfaces and to each other.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms will form on virtually every non-shedding surface in non-sterile aqueous or humid environments.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can grow in the most extreme environments: from, for example, the extremely hot, briny waters of hot springs ranging from very acidic to very alkaline, to frozen glaciers.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can be found on rocks and pebbles at the bottoms of most streams or rivers and often form on the surfaces of stagnant pools of water.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are important components of food chains in rivers and streams and are grazed by the aquatic invertebrates upon which many fish feed.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are found on the surface of and inside plants.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They can either contribute to crop disease or, as in the case of nitrogen-fixing rhizobia on root nodules, exist symbiotically with the plant.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Examples of crop diseases related to biofilms include citrus canker, Pierce's disease of grapes, and bacterial spot of plants such as peppers and tomatoes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Percolating filters in sewage treatment works are highly effective removers of pollutants from settled sewage liquor.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They work by trickling the liquid over a bed of hard material which is designed to have a very large surface area.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A complex biofilm develops on the surface of the medium which absorbs, adsorbs and metabolises the pollutants.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The biofilm grows rapidly and when it becomes too thick to retain its grip on the media it washes off and is replaced by newly grown film.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The washed off ("sloughed" off) film is settled out of the liquid stream to leave a highly purified effluent.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Slow sand filters are used in water purification for treating raw water to produce a potable product.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They work through the formation of a biofilm called the hypogeal layer or *Schmutzdecke* in the top few millimetres of the fine sand layer.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The *Schmutzdecke* is formed in the first 10–20 days of operation and consists of bacteria, fungi, protozoa, rotifera and a range of aquatic insect larvae.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] As an epigeal biofilm ages, more algae tend to develop and larger aquatic organisms may be present including some bryozoa, snails and annelid worms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The surface biofilm is the layer that provides the effective purification in potable water treatment, the underlying sand providing the support medium for this biological treatment layer.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] As water passes through the hypogeal layer, particles of foreign matter are trapped in the mucilaginous matrix and soluble organic material is adsorbed.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The contaminants are metabolised by the bacteria, fungi and protozoa.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The water produced from an exemplary slow sand filter is of excellent quality with 90–99% bacterial cell count reduction.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Plant-beneficial microbes can be categorized as plant growth-promoting rhizobacteria.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These plant growth-promoters colonize the roots of plants, and provide a wide range of beneficial functions for their host including nitrogen fixation, pathogen suppression, anti-fungal properties, and the breakdown of organic materials.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] One of these functions is the defense against pathogenic, soil-borne bacteria and fungi by way of induced systemic resistance (ISR) or induced systemic responses triggered by pathogenic microbes (pathogen-induced systemic acquired resistance).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Plant exudates act as chemical signals for host specific bacteria to colonize.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Rhizobacteria colonization steps include attractions, recognition, adherence, colonization, and growth.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacteria that have been shown to be beneficial and form biofilms include *Bacillus, Pseudomonas,* and *Azospirillum*.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms in the rhizosphere often result in pathogen or plant induced systemic resistances.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Molecular properties on the surface of the bacterium cause an immune response in the plant host.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These microbe associated molecules interact with receptors on the surface of plant cells, and activate a biochemical response that is thought to include several different genes at a number of loci.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Several other signaling molecules have been linked to both induced systemic responses and pathogen-induced systemic responses, such as jasmonic acid and ethylene.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Cell envelope components such as bacterial flagella and lipopolysaccharides, which are recognized by plant cells as components of pathogens.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Certain iron metabolites produced by *Pseudomonas* have also been shown to create an induced systemic response.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This function of the biofilm helps plants build stronger resistance to pathogens.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Plants that have been colonized by PGPR forming a biofilm have gained systemic resistances and are primed for defense against pathogens.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This means that the genes necessary for the production of proteins that work towards defending the plant against pathogens have been expressed, and the plant has a "stockpile" of compounds to release to fight off pathogens.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A primed defense system is much faster in responding to pathogen induced infection, and may be able to deflect pathogens before they are able to establish themselves.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Plants increase the production of lignin, reinforcing cell walls and making it difficult for pathogens to penetrate into the cell, while also cutting off nutrients to already infected cells, effectively halting the invasion.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They produce antimicrobial compounds such as phytoalexins, chitinases, and proteinase inhibitors, which prevent the growth of pathogens.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These functions of disease suppression and pathogen resistance ultimately lead to an increase in agricultural production and a decrease in the use of chemical pesticides, herbicides, and fungicides because there is a reduced amount of crop loss due to disease.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Studies in 2003 discovered that the immune system supports biofilm development in the large intestine.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This was supported mainly with the fact that the two most abundantly produced molecules by the immune system also support biofilm production and are associated with the biofilms developed in the gut.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This is especially important because the appendix holds a mass amount of these bacterial biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This discovery helps to distinguish the possible function of the appendix and the idea that the appendix can help reinoculate the gut with good gut flora.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] However, modified or disrupted states of biofilms in the gut have been connected to diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In the human environment, biofilms can grow in showers very easily since they provide a moist and warm environment for them to thrive.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Mold biofilms on ceilings may form due to roof leaks.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] They can form inside water and sewage pipes and cause clogging and corrosion.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] On floors and counters, they can make sanitation difficult in food preparation areas.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In cooling- or heating-water systems, they are known to reduce heat transfer.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms in marine engineering systems, such as pipelines of the offshore oil and gas industry, can lead to substantial corrosion problems.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Corrosion is mainly due to abiotic factors; however, at least 20% of corrosion is caused by microorganisms that are attached to the metal subsurface (i.e., microbially influenced corrosion).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacterial adhesion to boat hulls serves as the foundation for biofouling of seagoing vessels.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Once a film of bacteria forms, it is easier for other marine organisms such as barnacles to attach.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Such fouling can reduce maximum vessel speed by up to 20%, prolonging voyages and consuming fuel.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Time in dry dock for refitting and repainting reduces the productivity of shipping assets, and the useful life of ships is also reduced due to corrosion and mechanical removal (scraping) of marine organisms from ships' hulls.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Within the human body, biofilms are present on the teeth as dental plaque, where they may cause tooth decay and gum disease.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These biofilms can either be in an uncalcified state that can be removed by dental instruments, or a calcified state which is more difficult to remove.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Removal techniques can also include antimicrobials.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Dental plaque is an oral biofilm that adheres to the teeth and consists of many species of both bacteria and fungi (such as *Streptococcus mutans* and *Candida albicans*), embedded in salivary polymers and microbial extracellular products.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The accumulation of microorganisms subjects the teeth and gingival tissues to high concentrations of bacterial metabolites which results in dental disease.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilm on the surface of teeth is frequently subject to oxidative stress and acid stress.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Dietary carbohydrates can cause a dramatic decrease in pH in oral biofilms to values of 4 and below (acid stress).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A pH of 4 at body temperature of 37 °C causes depurination of DNA, leaving apurinic (AP) sites in DNA, especially loss of guanine.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Dental plaque biofilm can result in dental caries if it is allowed to develop over time.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] An ecologic shift away from balanced populations within the dental biofilm is driven by certain (cariogenic) microbiological populations beginning to dominate when the environment favors them.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The shift to an acidogenic, aciduric, and cariogenic microbiological population develops and is maintained by frequent consumption of fermentable dietary carbohydrate.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] By preventing the dental plaque biofilm from maturing or by returning it back to a non-cariogenic state, dental caries can be prevented and arrested.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This can be achieved through the behavioral step of reducing the supply of fermentable carbohydrates (i.e. sugar intake) and frequent removal of the biofilm (i.e., toothbrushing).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A peptide pheromone quorum sensing signaling system in *S. mutans* includes the competence stimulating peptide (CSP) that controls genetic competence.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Genetic competence is the ability of a cell to take up DNA released by another cell.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Competence can lead to genetic transformation, a form of sexual interaction, favored under conditions of high cell density and/or stress where there is maximal opportunity for interaction between the competent cell and the DNA released from nearby donor cells.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This system is optimally expressed when *S. mutans* cells reside in an actively growing biofilm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilm grown *S. mutans* cells are genetically transformed at a rate 10- to 600-fold higher than *S. mutans* growing as free-floating planktonic cells suspended in liquid.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] When the biofilm, containing *S. mutans* and related oral streptococci, is subjected to acid stress, the competence regulon is induced, leading to resistance to being killed by acid.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] As pointed out by Michod et al., transformation in bacterial pathogens likely provides for effective and efficient recombinational repair of DNA damages.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It appears that *S. mutans* can survive the frequent acid stress in oral biofilms, in part, through the recombinational repair provided by competence and transformation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Predator-prey interactions between biofilms and bacterivores, such as the soil-dwelling nematode *Caenorhabditis elegans,* had been extensively studied.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Via the production of sticky matrix and formation of aggregates, *Yersinia pestis* biofilms can prevent feeding by obstructing the mouth of *C. elegans*.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Moreover, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* biofilms can impede the slithering motility of *C. elegans*, termed as 'quagmire phenotype', resulting in trapping of *C. elegans* within the biofilms and preventing the exploration of nematodes to feed on susceptible biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This significantly reduced the ability of predator to feed and reproduce, thereby promoting the survival of biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* biofilms can also mask their chemical signatures, where they reduced the diffusion of quorum sensing molecules into the environment and prevented the detection of *C. elegans*.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In natural environments, biofilms act as highly organized systems with varying complex structures that allow them to carry out many ecological functions.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilm formation in natural environments contribute to biological processes including organic matter cycling and ecosystem respiration.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Due to these processes, microbial biofilms contribute to biogeochemical fluxes and are recognized as major contributors to global carbon and nitrogen fluxes, releasing large amounts of carbon dioxide and nitrogen gas into the atmosphere.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The complex and diverse nature of microbial consortia between communities regulate the chemical exchange between the lithosphere, hydrosphere, and atmosphere.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Due to biofilms being one of the most widely distributed and diverse microbial communities, they are an important contributor to the cycling of ecological nutrients including nitrogen, phosphorus, carbon, and oxygen.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Microbial biofilms vary in their ability to mediate these nutrient processes depending on environmental conditions and the taxonomic and functional composition of the community.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The nitrogen cycle is mediated by microorganisms, and biofilms play an important role in nitrogen fixation, nitrification, denitrification, and ammonification.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] There is an abundance of nitrogen present on Earth, however, the majority of nitrogen present is not directly usable by most living organisms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can play an important role in nitrogen cycling because their specialized structures create nutrient gradients that support nitrogen transformations.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Microbial derived carbon has a strong influence on the composition of soil organic carbon and provides the necessary substrates for soil respiration and methanogenesis.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In aquatic environments, biofilms can influence carbon cycling by retaining organic matter within the extracellular matrix.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] During this process, coupled carbon fixation and respiration occurs within the matrix.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Photosynthetic microorganisms within biofilms can fix CO2, while nearby heterotrophs metabolize organic compounds, allowing for fluctuations in carbon levels within the same structured microbial community.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Microbial activity within a biofilm matrix can promote biomineralization, including the precipitation of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This process is influenced by the interactions of microbial metabolism and diffusion gradient in pH levels, dissolved inorganic carbon, oxygen, and ion concentration that develop within the microbial matrix.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In biofilms, carbon dioxide uptake can raise local pH and shift carbonate chemistry in ways that favor CaCO3 precipitation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The precipitation caused by biomineralization affects many biofilm characteristics including, detachment, permeability, community metabolism, strength, and susceptibility.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Stromatolites are layered accretionary structures formed in shallow water by the trapping, binding and cementation of sedimentary grains by microbial biofilms, especially of cyanobacteria.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Stromatolites include some of the most ancient records of life on Earth, and are still forming today.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Modern stromatolites display microbial communities in distinct layers and give evidence of the biogeochemical nutrient cycles, allowing for interpretation of ecological characteristics within a biofilm matrix.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Stromatolite growth is initiated by the accumulation and entrapment of sediments formed through the process of biomineralization.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The layering of different microbial members within stromatolites is due to the timeline of different metabolic processes that occur within a biofilm matrix.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Due to this series of formation, physical and chemical characteristics can occur from the coupling of several redox reactions.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This metabolic process makes stromatolites a useful model for understanding how biofilm structure influences ecosystem scale geochemical processes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Many different bacteria form biofilms, including gram-positive (e.g.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Bacillus* spp, *Listeria monocytogenes*, *Staphylococcus* spp, and lactic acid bacteria, including *Lactobacillus plantarum* and *Lactococcus lactis*) and gram-negative species (e.g.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Escherichia coli*, or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Cyanobacteria also form biofilms in aquatic environments.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are formed by bacteria that colonize plants, e.g.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Pseudomonas putida*, *Pseudomonas fluorescens*, and related pseudomonads which are common plant-associated bacteria found on leaves, roots, and in the soil, and the majority of their natural isolates form biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Several nitrogen-fixing symbionts of legumes such as *Rhizobium leguminosarum* and *Sinorhizobium meliloti* form biofilms on legume roots and other inert surfaces.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Along with bacteria, biofilms are also generated by archaea and by a range of eukaryotic organisms, including fungi e.g.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Cryptococcus laurentii* and microalgae.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Among microalgae, one of the main progenitors of biofilms are diatoms, which colonise both fresh and marine environments worldwide.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] For other species in disease-associated biofilms and biofilms arising from eukaryotes, see below.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms have been found to be involved in a wide variety of microbial infections in the body, by one estimate 80% of all infections.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The first visual evidence of a biofilm was recorded after spine surgery.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It was found that in the absence of clinical presentation of infection, impregnated bacteria could form a biofilm around an implant, and this biofilm can remain undetected via contemporary diagnostic methods, including swabbing.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Implant biofilm is frequently present in "aseptic" pseudarthrosis cases.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Furthermore, it has been noted that bacterial biofilms may impair cutaneous wound healing and reduce topical antibacterial efficiency in healing or treating infected skin wounds.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The diversity of *P. aeruginosa* cells within a biofilm is thought to make it harder to treat the infected lungs of people with cystic fibrosis.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Early detection of biofilms in wounds is crucial to successful chronic wound management.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Although many techniques have developed to identify planktonic bacteria in viable wounds, few have been able to quickly and accurately identify bacterial biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Future studies are needed to find means of identifying and monitoring biofilm colonization at the bedside to permit timely initiation of treatment.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It has been shown that biofilms are present on the removed tissue of 80% of patients undergoing surgery for chronic sinusitis.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The patients with biofilms were shown to have been denuded of cilia and goblet cells, unlike the controls without biofilms who had normal cilia and goblet cell morphology.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms were also found on samples from two of 10 healthy controls mentioned.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The species of bacteria from intraoperative cultures did not correspond to the bacteria species in the biofilm on the respective patient's tissue.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In other words, the cultures were negative though the bacteria were present.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] New staining techniques are being developed to differentiate bacterial cells growing in living animals, e.g. from tissues with allergy-inflammations.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Research has shown that sub-therapeutic levels of β-lactam antibiotics induce biofilm formation in *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This sub-therapeutic level of antibiotic may result from the use of antibiotics as growth promoters in agriculture, or during the normal course of antibiotic therapy.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The biofilm formation induced by low-level methicillin was inhibited by DNase, suggesting that the sub-therapeutic levels of antibiotic also induce extracellular DNA release.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilm formation of *P. aeruginosa*, along with other bacteria, is found in 90% of chronic wound infections, which leads to poor healing and high cost of treatment estimated at more than US$25 billion every year in the United States.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In order to minimize the *P. aeruginosa* infection, host epithelial cells secrete antimicrobial peptides, such as lactoferrin, to prevent the formation of the biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It has been proposed that competence development and biofilm formation is an adaptation of *S. pneumoniae* to survive the defenses of the host.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In particular, the host's polymorphonuclear leukocytes produce an oxidative burst to defend against the invading bacteria, and this response can kill bacteria by damaging their DNA.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Competent *S. pneumoniae* in a biofilm have the survival advantage that they can more easily take up transforming DNA from nearby cells in the biofilm to use for recombinational repair of oxidative damages in their DNA.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Competent *S. pneumoniae* can also secrete an enzyme (murein hydrolase) that destroys non-competent cells (fratricide) causing DNA to be released into the surrounding medium for potential use by the competent cells.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The multi-target mechanism of action involves outer membrane permeabilization followed by biofilm disruption triggered by the inhibition of efflux pump activity and interactions with extracellular and intracellular nucleic acids.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Research suggests that biofilm formation by S. marcescens is a process controlled by both nutrient cues and the quorum-sensing system.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Quorum sensing influences the bacterium's ability to adhere to surfaces and establish mature biofilms, whereas the availability of specific nutrients can enhance or inhibit biofilm development.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Efforts to control and prevent biofilm formation by *S. marcescens* involve the use of antimicrobial coatings on medical devices, the development of targeted biofilm disruptors, and improved sterilization protocols.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Further research into the molecular mechanisms governing *S. marcescens* biofilm formation and persistence is crucial for developing effective strategies to combat its associated risks.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The use of indole compounds has been studied to be used as protection against biofilm formation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It is suggested that around two-thirds of bacterial infections in humans involve biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Infections associated with the biofilm growth usually are challenging to eradicate.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This is mostly due to the fact that mature biofilms display antimicrobial tolerance, and immune response evasions.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms often form on the inert surfaces of implanted devices such as catheters, prosthetic cardiac valves and intrauterine devices.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Some of the most difficult infections to treat are those associated with the use of medical devices.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The rapidly expanding worldwide industry for biomedical devices and tissue engineering related products is already at $180 billion per year, yet this industry continues to suffer from microbial colonization.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] No matter the sophistication, microbial infections can develop on all medical devices and tissue engineering constructs.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] 60–70% of hospital-acquired infections are associated with the implantation of a biomedical device.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This leads to 2 million cases annually in the U.S., costing the healthcare system over $5 billion in additional healthcare expenses.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The level of antibiotic resistance in a biofilm is much greater than that of non-biofilm bacteria, and can be as much as 5,000 times greater.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The extracellular matrix of biofilm is considered one of the leading factors that can reduce the penetration of antibiotics into a biofilm structure and contributes to antibiotic resistance.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Further, it has been demonstrated that the evolution of resistance to antibiotics may be affected by the biofilm lifestyle.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacteriophage therapy can disperse the biofilm generated by antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] It has been shown that the introduction of a small current of electricity to the liquid surrounding a biofilm, together with small amounts of antibiotic can reduce the level of antibiotic resistance to levels of non-biofilm bacteria.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] This is termed the **bioelectric effect**.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The application of a small DC current on its own can cause a biofilm to detach from its surface.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] A study showed that the type of current used made no difference to the bioelectric effect.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Microbial biofilms have many industrial applications such as the detoxification of environmental pollutants and wastewater treatments.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Through these biogeochemical processes, complex and versatile microbial structures serve as an efficient way to detoxify organic pollutants and remove nutrients from waste waters.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can also be harnessed for constructive purposes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] For example, many sewage treatment plants include a secondary treatment stage in which waste water passes over biofilms grown on filters, which extract and digest organic compounds.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In such biofilms, bacteria are mainly responsible for removal of organic matter (BOD), while protozoa and rotifers are mainly responsible for removal of suspended solids (SS), including pathogens and other microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Slow sand filters rely on biofilm development in the same way to filter surface water from lake, spring or river sources for drinking purposes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] What is regarded as clean water is effectively a waste material to these microcellular organisms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms can help eliminate petroleum oil from contaminated oceans or marine systems.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The oil is eliminated by the hydrocarbon-degrading activities of communities of hydrocarbonoclastic bacteria (HCB).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are used in microbial fuel cells (MFCs) to generate electricity from a variety of starting materials, including complex organic waste and renewable biomass.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms are also relevant for the improvement of metal dissolution in bioleaching industry, and aggregation of microplastics pollutants for convenient removal from the environment.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms have become problematic in several food industries due to the ability to form on plants and during industrial processes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacteria can survive long periods of time in water, animal manure, and soil, causing biofilm formation on plants or in the processing equipment.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The buildup of biofilms can affect the heat flow across a surface and increase surface corrosion and frictional resistance of fluids.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These can lead to a loss of energy in a system and overall loss of products.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Along with economic problems, biofilm formation on food poses a health risk to consumers due to the ability to make the food more resistant to disinfectants As a result, from 1996 to 2010 the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimated 48 million foodborne illnesses per year.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Biofilms have been connected to about 80% of bacterial infections in the United States.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In produce, microorganisms attach to the surfaces and biofilms develop internally.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] During the washing process, biofilms resist sanitization and allow bacteria to spread across the produce, especially via kitchen utensils.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The bacteria can spoil the products more readily and contaminated products pose a health risk to consumers.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] One species of bacteria that can be found in various industries and is a major cause of foodborne disease is *Salmonella*.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Large amounts of Salmonella contamination can be found in the poultry processing industry as about 50% of *Salmonella* strains can produce biofilms on poultry farms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Salmonella* increases the risk of foodborne illnesses when the poultry products are not cleaned and cooked correctly.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] *Salmonella* is also found in the seafood industry where biofilms form from seafood borne pathogens on the seafood itself as well as in water.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Shrimp products are commonly affected by *Salmonella* because of unhygienic processing and handling techniques The preparation practices of shrimp and other seafood products can allow for bacteria buildup on the products.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] New forms of cleaning procedures are being tested to reduce biofilm formation in these processes which will lead to safer and more productive food processing industries.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] These new forms of cleaning procedures also have a profound effect on the environment, often releasing toxic gases into the groundwater reservoirs.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] As a response to the aggressive methods employed in controlling biofilm formation, there are a number of novel technologies and chemicals under investigation that can prevent either the proliferation or adhesion of biofilm-secreting microbes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Latest proposed biomolecules presenting marked anti-biofilm activity include a range of metabolites such as bacterial rhamnolipids and even plant- and animal-derived alkaloids.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In shellfish and algal aquaculture, biofouling microbial species tend to block nets and cages and ultimately outcompete the farmed species for space and food.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Bacterial biofilms start the colonization process by creating microenvironments that are more favorable for biofouling species.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] In the marine environment, biofilms could reduce the hydrodynamic efficiency of ships and propellers, lead to pipeline blockage and sensor malfunction, and increase the weight of appliances deployed in seawater.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Numerous studies have shown that biofilm can be a reservoir for potentially pathogenic bacteria in freshwater aquaculture.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] Moreover, biofilms are important in establishing infections on the fish.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] As mentioned previously, biofilms can be difficult to eliminate even when antibiotics or chemicals are used in high doses.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p01] The role that biofilm plays as reservoirs of bacterial fish pathogens has not been explored in detail but it certainly deserves to be studied.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Along with bacteria, biofilms are often initiated and produced by eukaryotic microbes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] The biofilms produced by eukaryotes is usually occupied by bacteria and other eukaryotes alike, however the surface is cultivated and EPS is secreted initially by the eukaryote.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Both fungi and microalgae are known to form biofilms in such a way.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Biofilms of fungal origin are important aspects of human infection and fungal pathogenicity, as the fungal infection is more resistant to antifungals.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] In the environment, fungal biofilms are an area of ongoing research.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] One key area of research is fungal biofilms on plants.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] For example, in the soil, plant associated fungi including mycorrhiza have been shown to decompose organic matter and protect plants from bacterial pathogens.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Biofilms in aquatic environments are often founded by diatoms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] The exact purpose of these biofilms is unknown, however there is evidence that the EPS produced by diatoms facilitates both cold and salinity stress.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] These eukaryotes interact with a diverse range of other organisms within a region known as the phycosphere, but importantly are the bacteria associated with diatoms, as it has been shown that although diatoms excrete EPS, they only do so when interacting with certain bacteria species.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Horizontal gene transfer is the lateral transfer of genetic material between cellular organisms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] It happens frequently in prokaryotes, and less frequently in eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] In bacteria, horizontal gene transfer can occur through transformation (uptake of free floating DNA in the environment), transduction (virus mediated DNA uptake), or conjugation (transfer of DNA between pili structures of two adjacent bacteria).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Recent studies have also uncovered other mechanisms, such as membrane vesicle transmission or gene transfer agents.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Biofilms promote horizontal gene transfer in a variety of ways.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Bacterial conjugation has been shown to accelerate biofilm formation in difficult environment due to the robust connections established by the conjugative pili.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] These connections can often foster cross-species transfer events due to the diverse heterogeneity of many biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Additionally, biofilms are structurally confined by a polysaccharide matrix, providing the close spatial requirements for conjugation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Transformation is also frequently observed in biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Bacterial autolysis is a key mechanism in biofilm structural regulation, providing an abundant source of competent DNA primed for transformative uptake.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] In some instances, inter-biofilm quorum sensing can enhance the competence of free floating eDNA, further promoting transformation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Stx gene transfer through bacteriophage carriers has been witnessed within biofilms, which suggests that biofilms are also a suitable environment for transduction.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Membrane vesicles HGT occurs when released membrane vesicles (containing genetic information) fuse with a recipient bacteria, and release genetic material into the bacteria's cytoplasm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Recent research has revealed that membrane vesicle HGT can promote single-strain biofilm formation, yet the role membrane vesicle HGT plays in the formation of multistrain biofilms is still unknown.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] GTAs, or gene transfer agents, are phage-like particles produced by the host bacteria and contain random DNA fragments from the host bacteria genome.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] HGT within biofilms can confer antibiotic resistance or increased pathogenicity across the biofilms' population, promoting biofilm homeostasis.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Conjugative plasmids may encode biofilm-associated proteins, such as PtgA, PrgB, or PrgC which promote cell adhesion (required for early biofilm formation).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Genes encoding type III fimbriae are found in pOLA52 (*Klebsiella pneumoniae* plasmid) which promote conjugative-pilus-dependent biofilm formation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Transformation commonly occurs within biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] A phenomenon called fratricide can be seen among streptococcal species in which cell-wall degrading enzymes are released, lysing neighboring bacteria and releasing their DNA.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] This DNA can then be taken up by the surviving bacteria (transformation).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Competence stimulating peptides may play an important role in biofilm formation among *S. pneumoniae* and *S. mutans* as well.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Among *V. cholerae*, the competence pilus itself promotes cell aggregation through pilus-pilus interactions at the beginning of biofilm formation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Phage invasion may play a role in biofilm life cycles, lysing bacteria and releasing their eDNA, which strengthens biofilm structures and can be taken up by neighboring bacteria in transformation.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Biofilm destruction caused by the *E. coli* phage Rac and the *P. aeruginosa* prophage Pf4 causes detachment of cells from the biofilm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Detachment is a biofilm phenomenon which requires more study, but is hypothesized to proliferate the bacterial species that comprise the biofilm.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Membrane vesicle HGT has been witnessed occurring in marine environments, among *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Helicobacter pylori*, and among many other bacterial species.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Even though membrane vesicle HGT has been shown as a contributing factor in biofilm formation, research is still required to prove that membrane vesicle mediated HGT occurs within biofilms.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Membrane vesicle HGT has also been shown to modulate phage-bacteria interactions in *Bacillus subtilis* SPP1 phage-resistant cells (lacking the SPP1 receptor protein).
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Upon exposure to vesicles containing receptors, transduction of pBT163 (a cat-encoding plasmid) occurs, resulting in the expression of the SPP1 receptor protein, opening the receptive bacteria to future phage infection.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Recent research has shown that the archaeal species *H. volcanii* has some biofilm phenotypes similar to bacterial biofilms such as differentiation and HGT, which required cell-cell contact and involved formation of cytosolic bridges and cellular fusion events.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] There is a wide variety of biofilm cultivation devices to mimic natural or industrial environments.
[src:microbiology/biofilm-p02] Although it is important to consider that the particular experimental platform for biofilm research determines what kind of biofilm is cultivated and the data that can be extracted.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram staining differentiates bacteria by the chemical and physical properties of their cell walls.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram-positive cells have a thick layer of peptidoglycan in the cell wall that retains the primary stain, crystal violet.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram-negative cells have a thinner peptidoglycan layer that allows the crystal violet to wash out on addition of ethanol.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] They are stained pink or red by the counterstain, commonly safranin or fuchsine.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Lugol's iodine solution is always added after addition of crystal violet to form a stable complex with crystal violet that strengthens the bonds of the stain with the cell wall.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram staining is almost always the first step in the identification of a bacterial group.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] While Gram staining is a valuable diagnostic tool in both clinical and research settings, not all bacteria can be definitively classified by this technique.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] This gives rise to *gram-variable* and *gram-indeterminate* groups.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The method is named after its inventor, the Danish scientist Hans Christian Gram (1853–1938), who developed the technique while working with Carl Friedländer in the morgue of the city hospital in Berlin in 1884.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram devised his technique not for the purpose of distinguishing one type of bacterium from another but to make bacteria more visible in stained sections of lung tissue.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram noticed that some bacterial cells possessed noticeable resistance to decolorization.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Based on these observations, Gram developed the initial gram staining procedure, initially making use of Ehrlich's aniline-gentian violet, Lugol's iodine, absolute alcohol for decolorization, and Bismarck brown for counterstain.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] He published his method in 1884, and included in his short report the observation that the typhus bacillus did not retain the stain.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram did not initially make the distinction between Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria using his procedure.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram staining is a bacteriological laboratory technique used to differentiate bacterial species into two large groups (gram-positive and gram-negative) based on the physical properties of their cell walls.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram staining can also be used to diagnose a fungal infection.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram staining is not used to classify archaea, since these microorganisms yield widely varying responses that do not follow their phylogenetic groups.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram stains are performed on body fluid or biopsy when infection is suspected.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram stains yield results much more quickly than culturing, and are especially important when infection would make an important difference in the patient's treatment and prognosis; examples are cerebrospinal fluid for meningitis and synovial fluid for septic arthritis.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Carbol fuchsin is sometimes substituted for safranin since it more intensely stains anaerobic bacteria, but it is less commonly used as a counterstain.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Crystal violet (CV) dissociates in aqueous solutions into CV+ and chloride (Cl− ) ions.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] These ions penetrate the cell wall of both gram-positive and gram-negative cells.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The CV+ ion interacts with negatively charged components of bacterial cells and stains the cells purple.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Iodide (I− or I− 3) interacts with CV+ and forms large complexes of crystal violet and iodine (CV–I) within the inner and outer layers of the cell.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Iodine is often referred to as a mordant, but is a trapping agent that prevents the removal of the CV–I complex and, therefore, colors the cell.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] When a decolorizer such as alcohol or acetone is added, it interacts with the lipids of the cell membrane.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] A gram-negative cell loses its outer lipopolysaccharide membrane, and the inner peptidoglycan layer is left exposed.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The CV–I complexes are washed from the gram-negative cell along with the outer membrane.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] In contrast, a gram-positive cell becomes dehydrated from an ethanol treatment.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The large CV–I complexes become trapped within the gram-positive cell due to the multilayered nature of its peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The decolorization step is critical and must be timed correctly; the crystal violet stain is removed from both gram-positive and negative cells if the decolorizing agent is left on too long (a matter of seconds).
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] After decolorization, the gram-positive cell remains purple and the gram-negative cell loses its purple color.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Counterstain, which is usually positively charged safranin or basic fuchsine, is applied last to give decolorized gram-negative bacteria a pink or red color.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Both gram-positive bacteria and gram-negative bacteria pick up the counterstain.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The counterstain, however, is unseen on gram-positive bacteria because of the darker crystal violet stain.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram-positive bacteria generally have a single membrane (*monoderm*) surrounded by a thick peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] This rule is followed by two phyla: Bacillota (except for the classes Mollicutes and Negativicutes) and the Actinomycetota.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] In contrast, members of the Chloroflexota (green non-sulfur bacteria) are monoderms but possess a thin or absent (class Dehalococcoidetes) peptidoglycan and can stain negative, positive or indeterminate; members of the Deinococcota stain positive but are diderms with a thick peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The cell wall's strength is enhanced by teichoic acids, glycopolymeric substances embedded within the peptidoglycan.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Teichoic acids play multiple roles, such as generating the cell's net negative charge, contributing to cell wall rigidity and shape maintenance, and aiding in cell division and resistance to various stressors, including heat and salt.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Despite the density of the peptidoglycan layer, it remains relatively porous, allowing most substances to permeate.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] For larger nutrients, Gram-positive bacteria utilize exoenzymes, secreted extracellularly to break down macromolecules outside the cell.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Historically, the gram-positive forms made up the phylum Firmicutes, a name now used for the largest group.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] It includes many well-known genera such as *Lactobacillus, Bacillus*, *Listeria*, *Staphylococcus*, *Streptococcus*, *Enterococcus*, and *Clostridium*.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] It has also been expanded to include the Mollicutes, bacteria such as *Mycoplasma and Thermoplasma* that lack cell walls and so cannot be Gram-stained, but are derived from such forms.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Some bacteria have cell walls which are particularly adept at retaining stains.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] These will appear positive by Gram stain even though they are not closely related to other gram-positive bacteria.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] These are called acid-fast bacteria, and can only be differentiated from other gram-positive bacteria by special staining procedures.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram-negative bacteria generally possess a thin layer of peptidoglycan between two membranes (*diderm*).
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Lipopolysaccharide (LPS) is the most abundant antigen on the cell surface of most gram-negative bacteria, contributing up to 80% of the outer membrane of *E. coli* and *Salmonella*.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] These LPS molecules, consisting of the O-antigen or O-polysaccharide, core polysaccharide, and lipid A, serve multiple functions including contributing to the cell's negative charge and protecting against certain chemicals.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] LPS's role is critical in host-pathogen interactions, with the O-antigen eliciting an immune response and lipid A acting as an endotoxin.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Additionally, the outer membrane acts as a selective barrier, regulated by porins, transmembrane proteins forming pores that allow specific molecules to pass.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The space between the cell membrane and the outer membrane, known as the periplasm, contains periplasmic enzymes for nutrient processing.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] A significant structural component linking the peptidoglycan layer and the outer membrane is Braun's lipoprotein, which provides additional stability and strength to the bacterial cell wall.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Most bacterial phyla are gram-negative, including the cyanobacteria, green sulfur bacteria, and most Pseudomonadota (exceptions being some members of the Rickettsiales and the insect-endosymbionts of the Enterobacteriales).
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Some bacteria, after staining with the Gram stain, yield a gram-variable pattern: a mix of pink and purple cells are seen.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] In cultures of *Bacillus, Butyrivibrio*, and *Clostridium*, a decrease in peptidoglycan thickness during growth coincides with an increase in the number of cells that stain gram-negative.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] In addition, in all bacteria stained using the Gram stain, the age of the culture may influence the results of the stain.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Gram-indeterminate bacteria do not respond predictably to Gram staining and, therefore, cannot be determined as either gram-positive or gram-negative.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Examples include many species of *Mycobacterium*, including *Mycobacterium bovis*, *Mycobacterium leprae* and *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, the latter two of which are the causative agents of leprosy and tuberculosis, respectively.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Bacteria of the genus *Mycoplasma* lack a cell wall around their cell membranes, which means they do not stain by Gram's method and are resistant to the antibiotics that target cell wall synthesis.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The term *Gram staining* is derived from the surname of Hans Christian Gram; the eponym (Gram) is therefore capitalized but not the common noun (stain) as is usual for scientific terms.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] The initial letters of *gram-positive* and *gram-negative*, which are eponymous adjectives, can be either capital *G* or lowercase *g*, depending on what style guide (if any) governs the document being written.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Lowercase style is used by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and other style regimens such as the AMA style.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Dictionaries may use lowercase, uppercase, or both.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Uppercase *Gram-positive* or *Gram-negative* usage is also common in many scientific journal articles and publications.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] When articles are submitted to journals, each journal may or may not apply house style to the postprint version.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Preprint versions contain whichever style the author happened to use.
[src:microbiology/gram-stain] Even style regimens that use lowercase for the adjectives *gram-positive* and *gram-negative* still typically use capital for *Gram stain*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In practice, these terms are almost freely combined.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some microbes are heterotrophic (more precisely chemoorganoheterotrophic), using organic compounds as both carbon and energy sources.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Heterotrophic microbes live off of nutrients that they scavenge from living hosts (as commensals or parasites) or find in dead organic matter of all kind (saprophages).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Microbial metabolism is the main contribution for the bodily decay of all organisms after death.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Most pathogenic bacteria can be viewed as heterotrophic parasites of humans or the other eukaryotic species they affect.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Heterotrophic microbes are extremely abundant in nature and are responsible for the breakdown of large organic polymers such as cellulose, chitin or lignin which are generally indigestible to larger animals.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] There are many variations on this theme, as different organisms are able to degrade different polymers and secrete different waste products.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some organisms are even able to degrade more recalcitrant compounds such as petroleum compounds or pesticides, making them useful in bioremediation.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These basic pathways are well conserved because they are also involved in biosynthesis of many conserved building blocks needed for cell growth (sometimes in reverse direction).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] However, many bacteria and archaea utilize alternative metabolic pathways other than glycolysis and the citric acid cycle.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] A well-studied example is sugar metabolism via the keto-deoxy-phosphogluconate pathway (also called ED pathway) in *Pseudomonas*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Moreover, there is a third alternative sugar-catabolic pathway used by some bacteria, the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The metabolic diversity and ability of prokaryotes to use a large variety of organic compounds arises from the much deeper evolutionary history and diversity of prokaryotes, as compared to eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Therefore, it is not surprising that all mitrochondriate eukaryotes share metabolic properties with these Pseudomonadota.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Most microbes respire (use an electron transport chain), although oxygen is not the only terminal electron acceptor that may be used.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As discussed below, the use of terminal electron acceptors other than oxygen has important biogeochemical consequences.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Fermentation is a specific type of heterotrophic metabolism that uses organic carbon instead of oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This means that these organisms do not use an electron transport chain to oxidize NADH to NAD+ and therefore must have an alternative method of using this reducing power and maintaining a supply of NAD+ for the proper functioning of normal metabolic pathways (e.g. glycolysis).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As oxygen is not required, fermentative organisms are anaerobic.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many organisms can use fermentation under anaerobic conditions and aerobic respiration when oxygen is present.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These organisms are facultative anaerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] To avoid the overproduction of NADH, obligately fermentative organisms usually do not have a complete citric acid cycle.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Instead of using an ATP synthase as in respiration, ATP in fermentative organisms is produced by substrate-level phosphorylation where a phosphate group is transferred from a high-energy organic compound to ADP to form ATP.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As a result of the need to produce high energy phosphate-containing organic compounds (generally in the form of Coenzyme A-esters) fermentative organisms use NADH and other cofactors to produce many different reduced metabolic by-products, often including hydrogen gas (H 2).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These reduced organic compounds are generally small organic acids and alcohols derived from pyruvate, the end product of glycolysis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Examples include ethanol, acetate, lactate, and butyrate.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Fermentative organisms are very important industrially and are used to make many different types of food products.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The different metabolic end products produced by each specific bacterial species are responsible for the different tastes and properties of each food.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Not all fermentative organisms use substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Instead, some organisms are able to couple the oxidation of low-energy organic compounds directly to the formation of a proton motive force or sodium-motive force and therefore ATP synthesis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Examples of these unusual forms of fermentation include succinate fermentation by *Propionigenium modestum* and oxalate fermentation by *Oxalobacter formigenes*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These reactions are extremely low-energy yielding.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Humans and other higher animals also use fermentation to produce lactate from excess NADH, although this is not the major form of metabolism as it is in fermentative microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Methylotrophy refers to the ability of an organism to use C1-compounds as energy sources.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These compounds include methanol, methyl amines, formaldehyde, and formate.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Several other less common substrates may also be used for metabolism, all of which lack carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Examples of methylotrophs include the bacteria *Methylomonas* and *Methylobacter*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Methanotrophs are a specific type of methylotroph that are also able to use methane (CH 4) as a carbon source by oxidizing it sequentially to methanol (CH 3OH), formaldehyde (CH 2O), formate (HCOO− ), and carbon dioxide CO2 initially using the enzyme methane monooxygenase.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As oxygen is required for this process, all (conventional) methanotrophs are obligate aerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Reducing power in the form of quinones and NADH is produced during these oxidations to produce a proton motive force and therefore ATP generation.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In addition to aerobic methylotrophy, methane can also be oxidized anaerobically.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This occurs by a consortium of sulfate-reducing bacteria and relatives of methanogenic Archaea working syntrophically (see below).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Little is currently known about the biochemistry and ecology of this process.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Methanogenesis is the biological production of methane.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] It is carried out by methanogens, strictly anaerobic Archaea such as *Methanococcus*, *Methanocaldococcus*, *Methanobacterium*, *Methanothermus*, *Methanosarcina*, *Methanosaeta* and *Methanopyrus*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The biochemistry of methanogenesis is unique in nature in its use of a number of unusual cofactors to sequentially reduce methanogenic substrates to methane, such as coenzyme M and methanofuran.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These cofactors are responsible (among other things) for the establishment of a proton gradient across the outer membrane thereby driving ATP synthesis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Several types of methanogenesis occur, differing in the starting compounds oxidized.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some methanogens reduce carbon dioxide (CO2) to methane (CH 4) using electrons (most often) from hydrogen gas (H 2) chemolithoautotrophically.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These methanogens can often be found in environments containing fermentative organisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This type of syntrophic relationship is specifically known as interspecies hydrogen transfer.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] A second group of methanogens use methanol (CH 3OH) as a substrate for methanogenesis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These are chemoorganotrophic, but still autotrophic in using CO2 as only carbon source.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The biochemistry of this process is quite different from that of the carbon dioxide-reducing methanogens.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Lastly, a third group of methanogens produce both methane and carbon dioxide from acetate (CH 3COO− ) with the acetate being split between the two carbons.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These acetate-cleaving organisms are the only chemoorganoheterotrophic methanogens.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] All autotrophic methanogens use a variation of the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway to fix CO2 and obtain cellular carbon.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Syntrophy, in the context of microbial metabolism, refers to the pairing of multiple species to achieve a chemical reaction that, on its own, would be energetically unfavorable.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The best studied example of this process is the oxidation of fermentative end products (such as acetate, ethanol and butyrate) by organisms such as *Syntrophomonas*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Alone, the oxidation of butyrate to acetate and hydrogen gas is energetically unfavorable.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Conversely, the available free energy from methanogenesis is lowered from ΔGº'= -131 kJ/mol under standard conditions to ΔG' = -17 kJ/mol at 10−5 atm hydrogen.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This is an example of intraspecies hydrogen transfer.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In this way, low energy-yielding carbon sources can be used by a consortium of organisms to achieve further degradation and eventual mineralization of these compounds.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These reactions help prevent the excess sequestration of carbon over geologic time scales, releasing it back to the biosphere in usable forms such as methane and CO2.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Aerobic metabolism occurs in Bacteria, Archaea and Eucarya.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Although most bacterial species are anaerobic, many are facultative or obligate aerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The majority of archaeal species live in extreme environments that are often highly anaerobic.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] There are, however, several cases of aerobic archaea such as Halobacterium, Thermoplasma, Sulfolobus and Yymbaculum.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Most of the known eukaryotes carry out aerobic metabolism within their mitochondria which is an organelle that had a symbiogenesis origin from prokarya .
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] All aerobic organisms contain oxidases of the cytochrome oxidase super family, but some members of the Pseudomonadota (*E. coli* and *Acetobacter*) can also use an unrelated cytochrome bd complex as a respiratory terminal oxidase.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] While aerobic organisms during respiration use oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor, anaerobic organisms use other electron acceptors.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These inorganic compounds release less energy in cellular respiration, which leads to slower growth rates than aerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many facultative anaerobes can use either oxygen or alternative terminal electron acceptors for respiration depending on the environmental conditions.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Most respiring anaerobes are heterotrophs, although some do live autotrophically.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] All of the processes described below are dissimilative, meaning that they are used during energy production and not to provide nutrients for the cell (assimilative).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Assimilative pathways for many forms of anaerobic respiration are also known.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Denitrification is the utilization of nitrate (NO− 3) as a terminal electron acceptor.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] It is a widespread process that is used by many members of the Pseudomonadota.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many facultative anaerobes use denitrification because nitrate, like oxygen, has a high reduction potential.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many denitrifying bacteria can also use ferric iron (Fe3+ ) and some organic electron acceptors.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Denitrification involves the stepwise reduction of nitrate to nitrite (NO− 2), nitric oxide (NO), nitrous oxide (N 2O), and dinitrogen (N 2) by the enzymes nitrate reductase, nitrite reductase, nitric oxide reductase, and nitrous oxide reductase, respectively.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Protons are transported across the membrane by the initial NADH reductase, quinones, and nitrous oxide reductase to produce the electrochemical gradient critical for respiration.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *E. coli*) only produce nitrate reductase and therefore can accomplish only the first reduction leading to the accumulation of nitrite.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *Paracoccus denitrificans* or *Pseudomonas stutzeri*) reduce nitrate completely.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Complete denitrification is an environmentally significant process because some intermediates of denitrification (nitric oxide and nitrous oxide) are important greenhouse gases that react with sunlight and ozone to produce nitric acid, a component of acid rain.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Denitrification is also important in biological wastewater treatment where it is used to reduce the amount of nitrogen released into the environment thereby reducing eutrophication.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Denitrification can be determined via a nitrate reductase test.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Dissimilatory sulfate reduction is a relatively energetically poor process used by many Gram-negative bacteria found within the Thermodesulfobacteriota, Gram-positive organisms relating to *Desulfotomaculum* or the archaeon *Archaeoglobus*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Hydrogen sulfide (H 2S) is produced as a metabolic end product.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] For sulfate reduction electron donors and energy are needed.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many sulfate reducers are organotrophic, using carbon compounds such as lactate and pyruvate (among many others) as electron donors, while others are lithotrophic, using hydrogen gas (H 2) as an electron donor.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some unusual autotrophic sulfate-reducing bacteria (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *Desulfotignum phosphitoxidans*) can use phosphite (HPO− 3) as an electron donor whereas others (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] All sulfate-reducing organisms are strict anaerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Because sulfate is energetically stable, before it can be metabolized it must first be activated by adenylation to form APS (adenosine 5'-phosphosulfate) thereby consuming ATP.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The APS is then reduced by the enzyme APS reductase to form sulfite (SO2− 3) and AMP.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In organisms that use carbon compounds as electron donors, the ATP consumed is accounted for by fermentation of the carbon substrate.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The hydrogen produced during fermentation is actually what drives respiration during sulfate reduction.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Acetogenesis is a type of microbial metabolism that uses hydrogen (H 2) as an electron donor and carbon dioxide (CO2) as an electron acceptor to produce acetate, the same electron donors and acceptors used in methanogenesis (see above).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Bacteria that can autotrophically synthesize acetate are called homoacetogens.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Carbon dioxide reduction in all homoacetogens occurs by the acetyl-CoA pathway.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This pathway is also used for carbon fixation by autotrophic sulfate-reducing bacteria and hydrogenotrophic methanogens.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Often homoacetogens can also be fermentative, using the hydrogen and carbon dioxide produced as a result of fermentation to produce acetate, which is secreted as an end product.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Ferric iron (Fe3+ ) is a widespread anaerobic terminal electron acceptor both for autotrophic and heterotrophic organisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Electron flow in these organisms is similar to those in electron transport, ending in oxygen or nitrate, except that in ferric iron-reducing organisms the final enzyme in this system is a ferric iron reductase.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Model organisms include *Shewanella putrefaciens* and *Geobacter metallireducens*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Since some ferric iron-reducing bacteria (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *G. metallireducens*) can use toxic hydrocarbons such as toluene as a carbon source, there is significant interest in using these organisms as bioremediation agents in ferric iron-rich contaminated aquifers.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Although ferric iron is the most prevalent inorganic electron acceptor, a number of organisms (including the iron-reducing bacteria mentioned above) can use other inorganic ions in anaerobic respiration.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] While these processes may often be less significant ecologically, they are of considerable interest for bioremediation, especially when heavy metals or radionuclides are used as electron acceptors.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] A number of organisms, instead of using inorganic compounds as terminal electron acceptors, are able to use organic compounds to accept electrons from respiration.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] TMAO is a chemical commonly produced by fish, and when reduced to TMA produces a strong odor.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] DMSO is a common marine and freshwater chemical which is also odiferous when reduced to DMS.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Reductive dechlorination is the process by which chlorinated organic compounds are reduced to form their non-chlorinated endproducts.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As chlorinated organic compounds are often important (and difficult to degrade) environmental pollutants, reductive dechlorination is an important process in bioremediation.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Chemolithotrophy is a type of metabolism where energy is obtained from the oxidation of inorganic compounds.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Most chemolithotrophic organisms are also autotrophic.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] There are two major objectives to chemolithotrophy: the generation of energy (ATP) and the generation of reducing power (NADH).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many organisms are capable of using hydrogen (H 2) as a source of energy.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In these organisms, hydrogen is oxidized by a membrane-bound hydrogenase causing proton pumping via electron transfer to various quinones and cytochromes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In many organisms, a second cytoplasmic hydrogenase is used to generate reducing power in the form of NADH, which is subsequently used to fix carbon dioxide via the Calvin cycle.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Hydrogen-oxidizing organisms, such as *Cupriavidus necator* (formerly *Ralstonia eutropha*), often inhabit oxic-anoxic interfaces in nature to take advantage of the hydrogen produced by anaerobic fermentative organisms while still maintaining a supply of oxygen.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Sulfur oxidation involves the oxidation of reduced sulfur compounds (such as sulfide H 2S), inorganic sulfur (S), and thiosulfate (S 2O2− 3) to form sulfuric acid (H 2SO 4).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] A classic example of a sulfur-oxidizing bacterium is *Beggiatoa*, a microbe originally described by Sergei Winogradsky, one of the founders of environmental microbiology.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Generally, the oxidation of sulfide occurs in stages, with inorganic sulfur being stored either inside or outside of the cell until needed.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This two step process occurs because energetically sulfide is a better electron donor than inorganic sulfur or thiosulfate, allowing for a greater number of protons to be translocated across the membrane.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Sulfur-oxidizing organisms generate reducing power for carbon dioxide fixation via the Calvin cycle using reverse electron flow, an energy-requiring process that pushes the electrons against their thermodynamic gradient to produce NADH.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Biochemically, reduced sulfur compounds are converted to sulfite (SO2− 3) and subsequently converted to sulfate (SO2− 4) by the enzyme sulfite oxidase.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some organisms, however, accomplish the same oxidation using a reversal of the APS reductase system used by sulfate-reducing bacteria (see above).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In all cases the energy liberated is transferred to the electron transport chain for ATP and NADH production.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In addition to aerobic sulfur oxidation, some organisms (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *Thiobacillus denitrificans*) use nitrate (NO− 3) as a terminal electron acceptor and therefore grow anaerobically.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Ferrous iron is a soluble form of iron that is stable at extremely low pHs or under anaerobic conditions.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Under aerobic, moderate pH conditions ferrous iron is oxidized spontaneously to the ferric (Fe3+ ) form and is hydrolyzed abiotically to insoluble ferric hydroxide (Fe(OH) 3).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] There are three distinct types of ferrous iron-oxidizing microbes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The first are acidophiles, such as the bacteria *Acidithiobacillus ferrooxidans* and *Leptospirillum ferrooxidans*, as well as the archaeon *Ferroplasma*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These microbes oxidize iron in environments that have a very low pH and are important in acid mine drainage.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The second type of microbes oxidize ferrous iron at near-neutral pH.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These micro-organisms (for example *Gallionella ferruginea*, *Leptothrix ochracea*, or *Mariprofundus ferrooxydans*) live at the oxic-anoxic interfaces and are microaerophiles.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The third type of iron-oxidizing microbes are anaerobic photosynthetic bacteria such as Rhodopseudomonas, which use ferrous iron to produce NADH for autotrophic carbon dioxide fixation.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Biochemically, aerobic iron oxidation is a very energetically poor process which therefore requires large amounts of iron to be oxidized by the enzyme rusticyanin to facilitate the formation of proton motive force.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Like sulfur oxidation, reverse electron flow must be used to form the NADH used for carbon dioxide fixation via the Calvin cycle.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Nitrification is the process by which ammonia (NH 3) is converted to nitrate (NO− 3).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Nitrification is actually the net result of two distinct processes: oxidation of ammonia to nitrite (NO− 2) by nitrosifying bacteria (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *Nitrosomonas*) and oxidation of nitrite to nitrate by the nitrite-oxidizing bacteria (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Both of these processes are extremely energetically poor leading to very slow growth rates for both types of organisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Biochemically, ammonia oxidation occurs by the stepwise oxidation of ammonia to hydroxylamine (NH 2OH) by the enzyme ammonia monooxygenase in the cytoplasm, followed by the oxidation of hydroxylamine to nitrite by the enzyme hydroxylamine oxidoreductase in the periplasm.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Electron and proton cycling are very complex but as a net result only one proton is translocated across the membrane per molecule of ammonia oxidized.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Nitrite oxidation is much simpler, with nitrite being oxidized by the enzyme nitrite oxidoreductase coupled to proton translocation by a very short electron transport chain, again leading to very low growth rates for these organisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Oxygen is required in both ammonia and nitrite oxidation, meaning that both nitrosifying and nitrite-oxidizing bacteria are aerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As in sulfur and iron oxidation, NADH for carbon dioxide fixation using the Calvin cycle is generated by reverse electron flow, thereby placing a further metabolic burden on an already energy-poor process.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In 2015, two groups independently showed the microbial genus *Nitrospira* is capable of complete nitrification (Comammox).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Anammox stands for anaerobic ammonia oxidation and the organisms responsible were relatively recently discovered, in the late 1990s.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This form of metabolism occurs in members of the Planctomycetota (e.g.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] "*Candidatus* Brocadia anammoxidans") and involves the coupling of ammonia oxidation to nitrite reduction.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As oxygen is not required for this process, these organisms are strict anaerobes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Hydrazine (N 2H 4 – rocket fuel) is produced as an intermediate during anammox metabolism.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] To deal with the high toxicity of hydrazine, anammox bacteria contain a hydrazine-containing intracellular organelle called the anammoxasome, surrounded by highly compact (and unusual) ladderane lipid membrane.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These lipids are unique in nature, as is the use of hydrazine as a metabolic intermediate.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Anammox organisms are autotrophs although the mechanism for carbon dioxide fixation is unclear.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Because of this property, these organisms could be used to remove nitrogen in industrial wastewater treatment processes.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Anammox has also been shown to have widespread occurrence in anaerobic aquatic systems and has been speculated to account for approximately 50% of nitrogen gas production in the ocean.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In July 2020 researchers report the discovery of chemolithoautotrophic bacterial culture that feeds on the metal manganese after performing unrelated experiments and named its bacterial species *Candidatus Manganitrophus noduliformans* and *Ramlibacter lithotrophicus*.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Many microbes (phototrophs) are capable of using light as a source of energy to produce ATP and organic compounds such as carbohydrates, lipids, and proteins.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Of these, algae are particularly significant because they are oxygenic, using water as an electron donor for electron transfer during photosynthesis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Phototrophic bacteria are found in the phyla "Cyanobacteria", Chlorobiota, Pseudomonadota, Chloroflexota, and Bacillota.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Along with plants these microbes are responsible for all biological generation of oxygen gas on Earth.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Because chloroplasts were derived from a lineage of the Cyanobacteria, the general principles of metabolism in these endosymbionts can also be applied to chloroplasts.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In addition to oxygenic photosynthesis, many bacteria can also photosynthesize anaerobically, typically using sulfide (H 2S) as an electron donor to produce sulfate.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Inorganic sulfur (S 0), thiosulfate (S 2O2− 3) and ferrous iron (Fe2+ ) can also be used by some organisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In addition to these organisms, some microbes (e.g. the Archaeon *Halobacterium* or the bacterium *Roseobacter*, among others) can utilize light to produce energy using the enzyme bacteriorhodopsin, a light-driven proton pump.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] However, there are no known Archaea that carry out photosynthesis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] As befits the large diversity of photosynthetic bacteria, there are many different mechanisms by which light is converted into energy for metabolism.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Different photosynthetic bacteria also contain different photosynthetic pigments, such as chlorophylls and carotenoids, allowing them to take advantage of different portions of the electromagnetic spectrum and thereby inhabit different niches.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some groups of organisms contain more specialized light-harvesting structures (e.g. phycobilisomes in Cyanobacteria and chlorosomes in Green sulfur and non-sulfur bacteria), allowing for increased efficiency in light utilization.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Biochemically, anoxygenic photosynthesis is very different from oxygenic photosynthesis.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Cyanobacteria (and by extension, chloroplasts) use the Z scheme of electron flow in which electrons eventually are used to form NADH.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Two different reaction centers (photosystems) are used and proton motive force is generated both by using cyclic electron flow and the quinone pool.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In anoxygenic photosynthetic bacteria, electron flow is cyclic, with all electrons used in photosynthesis eventually being transferred back to the single reaction center.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] A proton motive force is generated using only the quinone pool.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In heliobacteria, Green sulfur, and Green non-sulfur bacteria, NADH is formed using the protein ferredoxin, an energetically favorable reaction.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In purple bacteria, NADH is formed by reverse electron flow due to the lower chemical potential of this reaction center.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] In all cases, however, a proton motive force is generated and used to drive ATP production via an ATPase.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Most photosynthetic microbes are autotrophic, fixing carbon dioxide via the Calvin cycle.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] *Chloroflexus*) are photoheterotrophs, meaning that they use organic carbon compounds as a carbon source for growth.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Some photosynthetic organisms also fix nitrogen (see below).
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Nitrogen is an element required for growth by all biological systems.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] While extremely common (80% by volume) in the atmosphere, dinitrogen gas (N 2) is generally biologically inaccessible due to its high activation energy.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Throughout all of nature, only specialized bacteria and Archaea are capable of nitrogen fixation, converting dinitrogen gas into ammonia (NH 3), which is easily assimilated by all organisms.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] These prokaryotes, therefore, are very important ecologically and are often essential for the survival of entire ecosystems.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] This is especially true in the ocean, where nitrogen-fixing cyanobacteria are often the only sources of fixed nitrogen, and in soils, where specialized symbioses exist between legumes and their nitrogen-fixing partners to provide the nitrogen needed by these plants for growth.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Nitrogen fixation can be found distributed throughout nearly all bacterial lineages and physiological classes but is not a universal property.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] Because the enzyme nitrogenase, responsible for nitrogen fixation, is very sensitive to oxygen which will inhibit it irreversibly, all nitrogen-fixing organisms must possess some mechanism to keep the concentration of oxygen low.
[src:microbiology/microbial-metabolism] The production and activity of nitrogenases is very highly regulated, both because nitrogen fixation is an extremely energetically expensive process (16–24 ATP are used per N 2 fixed) and due to the extreme sensitivity of the nitrogenase to oxygen.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The organisms that constitute the microbial world are characterized as either prokaryotes or eukaryotes.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Eukaryotic microorganisms possess membrane-bound organelles and include fungi and protists, whereas prokaryotic organisms are conventionally classified as lacking membrane-bound organelles and include Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Microbiologists traditionally relied on culture, staining, and microscopy for the isolation and identification of microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] However, less than 1% of the microorganisms present in common environments can be cultured in isolation using current means.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] With the emergence of biotechnology, microbiologists currently rely on molecular biology tools such as DNA sequence-based identification, for example, the 16S rRNA gene sequence used for bacterial identification.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Viruses have been variably classified as organisms because they have been considered either very simple microorganisms or very complex molecules.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Prions, never considered microorganisms, have been investigated by virologists; however, as the clinical effects traced to them were originally presumed due to chronic viral infections, virologists took a search—discovering "infectious proteins".
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The existence of microorganisms was predicted many centuries before they were first observed, for example by the Jains in India, and by Marcus Terentius Varro in ancient Rome.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The first recorded microscope observation was of the fruiting bodies of moulds, by Robert Hooke in 1666, but the Jesuit priest Athanasius Kircher was likely the first to see microbes, which he mentioned observing in milk and putrid material in 1658.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Antonie van Leeuwenhoek and Louis Pasteur is considered a father of microbiology as he observed and experimented with microscopic organisms in the 1670s, using simple microscopes of his design.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Scientific microbiology developed in the 19th century through the work of Louis Pasteur and in medical microbiology Robert Koch.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The existence of microorganisms was hypothesized for many centuries before their actual discovery.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The existence of unseen microbiological life was postulated by Jainism which is based on Mahavira's teachings as early as 6th century BCE (599 BC - 527 BC).
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Paul Dundas notes that Mahavira asserted the existence of unseen microbiological creatures living in earth, water, air and fire.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Jain scriptures describe nigodas which are sub-microscopic creatures living in large clusters and having a very short life, said to pervade every part of the universe, even in tissues of plants and flesh of animals.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Persian scientists hypothesized the existence of microorganisms, such as Avicenna in his book *The Canon of Medicine*, Ibn Zuhr (also known as Avenzoar) who discovered scabies mites, and Al-Razi who gave the earliest known description of smallpox in his book *The Virtuous Life* (al-Hawi).
[src:microbiology/microbiology] In 1546, Girolamo Fracastoro proposed that epidemic diseases were caused by transferable seedlike entities that could transmit infection by direct or indirect contact, or vehicle transmission.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek, who lived most of his life in Delft, Netherlands, observed bacteria and other microorganisms using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] He is considered a father of microbiology as he used simple single-lensed microscopes of his own design.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] While Van Leeuwenhoek is often cited as the first to observe microbes, Robert Hooke made his first recorded microscopic observation, of the fruiting bodies of moulds, in 1665.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] It has, however, been suggested that a Jesuit priest called Athanasius Kircher was the first to observe microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Kircher was among the first to design magic lanterns for projection purposes, and so he was well acquainted with the properties of lenses.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] He wrote "Concerning the wonderful structure of things in nature, investigated by Microscope" in 1646, stating "who would believe that vinegar and milk abound with an innumerable multitude of worms." He also noted that putrid material is full of innumerable creeping animalcules.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] He published his *Scrutinium Pestis* (Examination of the Plague) in 1658, stating correctly that the disease was caused by microbes, though what he saw was most likely red or white blood cells rather than the plague agent itself.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The field of bacteriology (later a subdiscipline of microbiology) was founded in the 19th century by Ferdinand Cohn, a botanist whose studies on algae and photosynthetic bacteria led him to describe several bacteria including *Bacillus* and *Beggiatoa*.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Cohn was also the first to formulate a scheme for the taxonomic classification of bacteria, and to discover endospores.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch were contemporaries of Cohn, and are often considered to be the fathers of modern microbiology and medical microbiology, respectively.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Pasteur is most famous for his series of experiments designed to disprove the then widely held theory of spontaneous generation, thereby solidifying microbiology's identity as a biological science.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] One of his students, Adrien Certes, is considered the founder of marine microbiology.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Pasteur also designed methods for food preservation (pasteurization) and vaccines against several diseases such as anthrax, fowl cholera and rabies.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Koch is best known for his contributions to the germ theory of disease, proving that specific diseases were caused by specific pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] He developed a series of criteria that have become known as the Koch's postulates.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Koch was one of the first scientists to focus on the isolation of bacteria in pure culture resulting in his description of several novel bacteria including *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, the causative agent of tuberculosis.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] While Pasteur and Koch are often considered the founders of microbiology, their work did not accurately reflect the true diversity of the microbial world because of their exclusive focus on microorganisms having direct medical relevance.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] It was not until the late 19th century and the work of Martinus Beijerinck and Sergei Winogradsky that the true breadth of microbiology was revealed.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Beijerinck made two major contributions to microbiology: the discovery of viruses and the development of enrichment culture techniques.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] While his work on the tobacco mosaic virus established the basic principles of virology, it was his development of enrichment culturing that had the most immediate impact on microbiology by allowing for the cultivation of a wide range of microbes with wildly different physiologies.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Winogradsky was the first to develop the concept of chemolithotrophy and to thereby reveal the essential role played by microorganisms in geochemical processes.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] He was responsible for the first isolation and description of both nitrifying and nitrogen-fixing bacteria.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] French-Canadian microbiologist Felix d'Herelle co-discovered bacteriophages in 1917 and was one of the earliest applied microbiologists.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Joseph Lister was the first to use phenol disinfectant on the open wounds of patients.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The branches of microbiology can be classified into applied sciences, or divided according to taxonomy, as is the case with bacteriology, parasitology, mycology, immunology, protozoology, virology, phycology, microbial genetics, and microbial ecology.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] There is considerable overlap between the specific branches of microbiology with each other and with other disciplines, and certain aspects of these branches can extend beyond the traditional scope of microbiology.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] A pure research branch of microbiology is termed cellular microbiology.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] While some people have fear of microbes due to the association of some microbes with various human diseases, many microbes are also responsible for numerous beneficial processes such as industrial fermentation (e.g. the production of alcohol, vinegar and dairy products) and antibiotic production.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Scientists have also exploited their knowledge of microbes to produce biotechnologically important enzymes such as Taq polymerase, reporter genes for use in other genetic systems and novel molecular biology techniques such as the yeast two-hybrid system.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Bacteria can be used for the industrial production of amino acids. organic acids, vitamin, proteins, antibiotics and other commercially used metabolites which are produced by microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] *Corynebacterium glutamicum* is one of the most important bacterial species with an annual production of more than two million tons of amino acids, mainly L-glutamate and L-lysine.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Since some bacteria have the ability to synthesize antibiotics, they are used for medicinal purposes, such as *Streptomyces* to make aminoglycoside antibiotics.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] A variety of biopolymers, such as polysaccharides, polyesters, and polyamides, are produced by microorganisms.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Microorganisms are used for the biotechnological production of biopolymers with tailored properties suitable for high-value medical application such as tissue engineering and drug delivery.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Microorganisms are for example used for the biosynthesis of xanthan, alginate, cellulose, cyanophycin, poly(gamma-glutamic acid), levan, hyaluronic acid, organic acids, oligosaccharides polysaccharide and polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Microorganisms are beneficial for microbial biodegradation or bioremediation of domestic, agricultural and industrial wastes and subsurface pollution in soils, sediments and marine environments.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The ability of each microorganism to degrade toxic waste depends on the nature of each contaminant.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Since sites typically have multiple pollutant types, the most effective approach to microbial biodegradation is to use a mixture of bacterial and fungal species and strains, each specific to the biodegradation of one or more types of contaminants.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Symbiotic microbial communities confer benefits to their human and animal hosts health including aiding digestion, producing beneficial vitamins and amino acids, and suppressing pathogenic microbes.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Some benefit may be conferred by eating fermented foods, probiotics (bacteria potentially beneficial to the digestive system) or prebiotics (substances consumed to promote the growth of probiotic microorganisms).
[src:microbiology/microbiology] The ways the microbiome influences human and animal health, as well as methods to influence the microbiome are active areas of research.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Research has suggested that microorganisms could be useful in the treatment of cancer.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Various strains of non-pathogenic clostridia can infiltrate and replicate within solid tumors.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Clostridial vectors can be safely administered and their potential to deliver therapeutic proteins has been demonstrated in a variety of preclinical models.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] Some bacteria are used to study fundamental mechanisms.
[src:microbiology/microbiology] An example of model bacteria used to study motility or the production of polysaccharides and development is *Myxococcus xanthus*.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] A **prokaryote** (/proʊˈkærioʊt, -ət/; less commonly spelled **procaryote**) is a microorganism whose usually single cell lacks a nucleus or other membrane-bound organelles.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The word *prokaryote* comes from the Ancient Greek πρό (*pró*), meaning "before", and κάρυον (*káruon*), meaning "nut" or "kernel".
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] In the earlier two-empire system, prokaryotes formed the empire **Prokaryota**.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] In the three-domain system, based upon molecular phylogenetics, prokaryotes are divided into two domains: Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] A third domain, Eukaryota, consists of organisms with cell nuclei.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Prokaryotes evolved before eukaryotes, and lack nuclei, mitochondria, and most of the other distinct organelles that characterize the eukaryotic cell.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Some unicellular prokaryotes, such as cyanobacteria, form colonies held together by biofilms, and large colonies can create multilayered microbial mats.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Prokaryotes are asexual, reproducing via binary fission.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Horizontal gene transfer is also common.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Molecular phylogenetics has provided insight into the interrelationships of the three domains of life.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The division between prokaryotes and eukaryotes reflects two very different levels of cellular organization; only eukaryotic cells have an enclosed nucleus that contains their DNA, and other membrane-bound organelles including mitochondria.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] More recently, the primary division has been seen as that between Archaea and Bacteria, since eukaryotes may be part of the archaean clade and have multiple homologies with other Archaea.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The cellular components of prokaryotes are not enclosed in membranes within the cytoplasm, like eukaryotic organelles.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Bacteria have microcompartments, quasi-organelles enclosed in protein shells such as encapsulin protein cages, while both bacteria and some archaea have gas vesicles.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] These are highly diverse, and contain homologues of the eukaryote proteins actin and tubulin.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The cytoskeleton provides the capability for movement within the cell.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Most prokaryotes are between 1 and 10 μm, but they vary in size from 0.2 μm in *Thermodiscus* spp. and *Mycoplasma genitalium* to 750 μm in *Thiomargarita namibiensis*.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Bacterial cells have various shapes, including spherical or ovoid cocci, e.g., *Streptococcus*; cylindrical bacilli, e.g., *Lactobacillus*; spiral bacteria, e.g., *Helicobacter*; or comma-shaped, e.g., *Vibrio*.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Archaea are mainly simple ovoids, but *Haloquadratum* is flat and square.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Bacteria and archaea reproduce through asexual reproduction, usually by binary fission.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Genetic exchange and recombination occur by horizontal gene transfer, not involving replication.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] DNA transfer between prokaryotic cells occurs in bacteria and archaea.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] In bacteria, gene transfer occurs by three processes.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] These are virus-mediated transduction; conjugation; and natural transformation.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Transduction of bacterial genes by bacteriophage viruses appears to reflect occasional errors during intracellular assembly of virus particles, rather than an adaptation of the host bacteria.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] There are at least three ways that it can occur, all involving the incorporation of some bacterial DNA in the virus, and from there to another bacterium.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Conjugation involves plasmids, allowing plasmid DNA to be transferred from one bacterium to another.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Infrequently, a plasmid may integrate into the host bacterial chromosome, and subsequently transfer part of the host bacterial DNA to another bacterium.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Natural bacterial transformation involves the transfer of DNA from one bacterium to another through the water around them.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] This is a bacterial adaptation for DNA transfer, because it depends on the interaction of numerous bacterial gene products.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The bacterium must first enter the physiological state called competence; in *Bacillus subtilis*, the process involves 40 genes.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The amount of DNA transferred during transformation can be as much as a third of the whole chromosome.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Transformation is common, occurring in at least 67 species of bacteria.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Among archaea, *Haloferax volcanii* forms cytoplasmic bridges between cells that transfer DNA between cells, while *Sulfolobus solfataricus* transfers DNA between cells by direct contact.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Exposure of *S. solfataricus* to agents that damage DNA induces cellular aggregation, perhaps enhancing homologous recombination to increase the repair of damaged DNA.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Prokaryotes are strictly unicellular, but most can form stable aggregate communities in biofilms.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Bacterial biofilms are formed by the secretion of extracellular polymeric substance (EPS).
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Myxobacteria have multicellular stages in their life cycles.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Biofilms may be structurally complex and may attach to solid surfaces, or exist at liquid-air interfaces.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Bacterial biofilms are often made up of microcolonies (dome-shaped masses of bacteria and matrix) separated by channels through which water may flow easily.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Microcolonies may join above the substratum to form a continuous layer.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] This structure functions as a simple circulatory system by moving water through the biofilm, helping to provide cells with oxygen which is often in short supply.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] The result approaches a multicellular organisation.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Differential cell expression, collective behavior, signaling (quorum sensing), programmed cell death, and discrete biological dispersal events all seem to point in this direction.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Bacterial biofilms may be 100 times more resistant to antibiotics than free-living unicells, making them difficult to remove from surfaces they have colonized.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Prokaryotes have diversified greatly throughout their long existence.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Their metabolism is far more varied than that of eukaryotes, leading to many highly distinct types.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] For example, prokaryotes may obtain energy by chemosynthesis.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Prokaryotes live nearly everywhere on Earth, including in environments as cold as soils in Antarctica, or as hot as undersea hydrothermal vents and land-based hot springs.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Some bacteria are pathogenic, causing disease in organisms including humans.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Some archaea and bacteria are extremophiles, thriving in harsh conditions, such as high temperatures (thermophiles) or high salinity (halophiles).
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Some archaeans are methanogens, living in anoxic environments and releasing methane.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Many archaea grow as plankton in the oceans.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Symbiotic prokaryotes live in or on the bodies of other organisms, including humans.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Prokaryotes have high populations in the soil, in the sea, and in undersea sediments.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] Soil prokaryotes are still heavily undercharacterized despite their easy proximity to humans and their tremendous economic importance to agriculture.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] A widespread model of the origin of life is that the first organisms were prokaryotes.
[src:microbiology/prokaryote] These developed from protocells, while the eukaryotes arose later in the history of life, by symbiogenesis: a merger of two prokaryotes, an archaean and an aerobic bacterium, created the first eukaryote, with aerobic mitochondria.
